segments.text: We were talking about improvements in training and leadership at A&M and the Cadet Corps, which we think has been real good, and elimination of some of the bad things and improvement of the leadership in counseling mainly.
And we think that the discipline training is much improved over what it was in 1945.
And this should really encourage more students to become cadets.
And the military services have improved the profession of militarism, too.
There's no disgrace in being connected with the military anymore like it used to be.
So this has an added impetus, but we still need to do some selling on this cadet program.
The civilian program, all in all, we believed, while I worked here, was real good, except for the fact that they didn't have the organization that the cadet corps did.
They were scattered because many of them have to live downtown.
You don't have contacts with them.
Many of them were married, and they don't have time to do student activities, participate in a lot of the programs.
But all in all, those are the kind of people that have spent their time studying and doing their schoolwork, and we think have improved the scholastic proficiency of married students as a whole.
And we kept records on this, incidentally, for a good number of years by categories.
And we found that the married students were making better progress as students than the single students, which is good for the institution, too.
And as a whole, these people were better satisfied than the single students.
We tried from time to time to encourage them to participate in the program, and some of them did.
But the thing that bothered us most was the fact that we couldn't ever get them all together.
We couldn't get them into a cohesive unit.
And even though we had programs set up for them, they didn't participate.
like we thought they should.
But we wanted it to be a voluntary thing.
And if they didn't want to participate, for instance, in things like the intramural program, OK.
If they didn't want to go out for athletics, if they didn't want to work on the MSC Council, fine.
But all in all, we think they've made good progress.
And despite the fact that some of them
more scroungy clothing, and weren't quite as meticulous about the dress.
We believed that this was a national trend, so we didn't fight it too hard.
We weren't very happy about it from time to time.
And I know Mr.
Rudder wasn't.
But there were certain limitations, too.

tried to keep them as clean as we could and as meticulous and we did this with the hope that they'd have pride in themselves and in the institution we think it worked up to a point and and incidentally we think that this helped to keep down some of the disorders that other university campuses had and we didn't
I spent a lot of time going around telling people that they couldn't have marches and sit-downs and things of this sort.
They wanted to do it.
Well, we discouraged it.
We did what we could, and we always policed them.
I don't like to use the word police, but we were there to see that trouble didn't erupt.
And we had plans made for assistance if we need to call on outside police people to come in.

And we kept close watch on groups that we thought might be subversive, like the SDS and other organizations that were very critical of various operations at the university, some of which were assisted by members of the staff.
And we knew who these members of the staff were and kept
institutional executives informed of this.
We improved the police operation and we think that campus security operations on Texas A&M campus are as good as you'll find in most institutions and the men are now getting some training.
This is required training and we've changed the attitude of the
operation.
I don't know whether you keep good men all the time or not, because this is a real problem.
The time you get a good group trained, they get better jobs in other institutions.
But they have a good program, and they've built a lot of good parking places for cars.
Not enough, but as much as they have money for, and they've changed the system of registration, and they're spending a lot of time with regular police work.
We have
a remarkably low crime rate on Texas A&M campus.
According to people in other agencies, we believe that it's much less than in most educational institutions even.
But of course, when you have 10,000, 12,000 people, you're going to have some thieves and would-be murderers and so on.
But we've had a good record so far.
We've had little disturbance.
And we think a lot of it has been due to the fact that we've had a lot of dedicated people on the campus, not only staff people, but a lot of students who have worked.
For instance, I remember one time that we got a threat that the SDS was going to block.
The cadet prayed when one of the outstanding generals came here.
And they had special guards meet him at the airport and all this kind of thing.
But a group of 200 students came.
And they had the names written down.
And they said, we'd like to take over this responsibility of protecting this general and the parade.
And we refused to let them have this because we didn't think it was fair to have a student group policing the campus for an emergency situation.
So we managed to get some key students posted around to keep us informed.
And we kept it from happening.
And this was a small group of about 12 students that we knew were members of the SDS.
Do you think one reason maybe we did remain fairly quiet during those days is that the students had come to a place where maybe somebody cared about what they did?
I think that's right.
I think most A&M students
have come to A&M because they felt like it was a sort of a conservative type institution that didn't believe in uprisings and rebellions.
There are ways of doing these things by proper process and students here have had the doors open enough for them to come in.
We've always felt like it's

There were a goodly number of the staff, teachers I'm talking about, faculty people who were interested in these programs too, and they assisted by even talking in classes from time to time, a few minutes about things that make an institution great.
And I know our counselors have worked on this, and the tactical officers did in the cadet corps, and the military science people teach this kind of thing.
They're a pretty good size staff too.
But the administration has generally been opposed to mob action and violence and let the students know this.
And the former students believe in this too.
They believe in this attitude.
Do you think maybe you have mob action and violence only when the students feel that they can no longer communicate with the
administration, and here where you have an open door policy, where if you feel like you need to tell somebody off, you can go do it.
You may be wrong in doing so, but the door is open to you.
And I would think since the administration has been fairly open, and you can go see almost anyone on this campus you want to see, that this has probably averted a lot of problems.
I think that's right, because I can remember many groups that
I went to see Mr. Gilchrist when he was president.
That's when we had a lot of unrest back right after the war.
And they could always see him.
They could always see the dean of students.
They could always see the dean of agriculture.
And if they wanted to have a group action, they got the executive committee together and let them point their own committee and come in and talk to the executive committee.
And I know they had assemblies over in Assembly Hall and in Guyon Hall, where people, where they could express their opinions.
And I think this has been continuous.
I think, all in all, that this attitude, too, you asked a question that I think that
communications help?
Well, yes, it does.
Now, of course, we felt like that some of these people in the SDS were planted here.
I know from time to time we found problems that other universities had about the black people, for instance.
And when Mr. Rutter decided
to admit some black people, they did it very quietly and notified these people to come at a certain time.
And they met in the registrar's office.
And Mr. Rutter had the registrar and the dean and the student affairs people meet with them and explain to them what the university would and could do.
But you people have to help.
So they registered these colored people before
anybody else arrested to avoid having them report to the line.
So they were arrested, no newspaper publicity, no radio, no television pictures, anything.
And these men got along real well with no trouble.
And when they ran into some difficulty, they always reported to the dean of students' office and reported what they'd found.
And then later we prevailed on the university to open up a swimming pool and the tennis courts and things like this for the black people.
When was this?
Do you remember?
Must have been about 1959 or 60.
I believe 60, but I'm not absolutely positive.
But I remember we had one man from Florida.
They were as happy as he could be because he said, this is the greatest thing that's happened for the black people, even though they didn't have very many of them.
And so far as I know, we've never had any problem with the black people at Texas A&M.
Now, we had one or two groups that wanted to demand, make certain demands on certain books and certain literature and certain classes, but Mr. Rutter and the library provided these things.
And I don't know how many teachers they have, but they have some black people now standing on the campus that are teaching.
Now, same thing happened with the foreign student program.
Back when I came in in 1945, there were about 50 or maybe 75 foreign students, mostly from Latin American countries.
And this thing was handled by two or three people.
The registrar's office did some of the work, and the
The dean of the college did some, and the rest of it was just done by the placement office, mainly advice.
And so we found that these people weren't very well accepted in a lot of cases by our own students, mainly because of communications again.
So President Bolton, when he was president, I don't even remember what year that was exactly,
asked our, the Dean of Students Office, to assume responsibility for our advisement of all foreign students and take over the whole program.

And the Student Affairs Office was bound with this thing and so we had to find out all the rules and regulations of the Immigration Service and the State Department and how to contact these people and we made associations with people in Houston and
San Antonio and El Paso and Washington, where we could contact them and get these people.
And we even set up programs where we'd have an orientation for these foreign groups when they'd come in.
And in spite of the fact that we've had some dissidents, like when Castro was in first power, some of the people from Cuba wanted to go down there and take over.
And we had to give them a lot of good advice, the best we had, of course, to keep them from getting into trouble.
And they wanted to bring Castro here, and we forbid it.
We had some foreign students that were opposed to the policies of the United States government and were very loud about this.
And we had tried to keep them in tow for peacemaking purposes.
And we had sessions with them.
We organized a foreign student club, and we met with them.
One of our staff always met with them and helped them arrange for some of their financial support and attended their special dinners and things of this sort.
And we finally got Mr.
Rudder to select Mr. Melcher as full-time foreign student advisor, because this grew and grew until he was

full-time job and Melcher did this entirely for a good number of years until about five or six years ago when he took on some other responsibilities for the dean of students and I understand that Mr. Melcher is still the foreign student advisor but has an assistant and this has helped not only the foreign students themselves but it's helped A&M students become acquainted with these people and their
heritage, heritages, and their customs, and getting a better attitude about worldwide situations.
I think this has been good for the university up to a point.
Now, there's some things that are wrong about it.
We recognize those, too.
We have noted, and this has been done by a lot of people, the university has
tremendously improved its housing program and its feeding services and health services in the past 20 years.
Because the university, up until about 1960, had an attitude that this was a poor man's school and should be kept that way.
And they just didn't want to raise any fees.
And they found out that it took more money and inflation was running prices up all the time.
So the university finally decided that the only way to get better food was to get more money from the students.
And the same thing about housing.
Buildings cost more, and we tried to institute a program of maintenance and keep them painted and cleaned and put down new equipment, new furniture, carpeting and tile flooring and whatever we could.
And we think this has had a
a good effect on the students.
A student can study and be happier in an attractive, clean place than he can in a makeshift proposition.
And they've even put in telephones and lounges and spent a lot of money on this.
Students don't sometimes use them as much as we think they ought to.

I guess they still don't, I know they didn't when I worked up here, because some of the lounges, but we spent a lot of money on the Memorial Student Center and put in a lot of good programs there and A&M provided the facility for the best education a guy can get at reasonable price.
I checked not too long ago for some people in Oklahoma who wanted to find out about Texas A&M and I found that the cost
average cost per student detection and essential cost is about half what it is in most institutions.
And a lot of institutions are as much as three and four times as much.
So even though it's gone up considerably, it's still not prohibitive.
And if a student wants to get work, he can get work to supplement his pay from home.

The university has modified a lot of its attitude, and I don't know for sure what the attitude is about discipline at this time, but we believed in law and order all along through the years, and students knew this.
If they didn't abide, they knew that they might get punished, and we tried to make it
swift and fair and told them.
We always told them why.
I don't know whether this has always been the policy of the university, but while all the years I worked up here, we told them why we did this.
We didn't just call them and say because we said so.
We explained to them why we did this.
Then they had an appeal.
We got the administration to send them an appeal panel.
As far as I know, it's still in operation.
And this is good because if the dean or the commandant
unfairly punishes a young man, he can appeal to the panel and he'll have nine or ten people listen.
And it's very unlikely that they're going to all be unfair, at least the majority of them, we think would be fair.
And, of course, he always, even after that, has an appeal to the president.
And the president has overruled the appeal panel a few times, not often, but a few times.
I don't know whether I've covered the thing or not.
There's a good number of other things that I can see.
When I first was a student, the health services were just sort of a first aid thing.
When I came back here to work in 1945, they didn't have adequate staff or facility, and it was modified quite a bit.
Now they have a new fine hospital.
I guess, with complete staff.
And I know the students can have inexpensive treatment.
A student that doesn't ever go to the hospital pays a fee, but this is what sick insurance amounts do.
I pay $230 a year for my wife and I.
Last year, we got back $40.
But if either one of us goes to hospital, we'd get it back.
That's what it's for.
It's a protection.
And it's very reasonable.
We did the same thing on publication.
When I came to work at A&M, they were having some great difficulties with publication.
They didn't really have a good organization.
One man ran it, and he reported it to the president.
I think the first man I knew was Roland Bing, and he was just out of the Army, was an A&M graduate, and had been a journal writer.
journalistic, I think he studied journalism when he was a student, I'm not sure.
But anyhow, he'd done some newspaper work and did public relations work in the Army.
So he was hired as administrator of the student publication program.
He did it all by himself.
But when he left here, he started having trouble because students still elected the editors of all the publications.

and sometimes this was a popularity contest not necessarily a matter of proficiency so the university appointed a board to advise them and sometimes the editors accused the board of being set up by the administration to censor which wasn't so because
I served on that publication board about five or six years, and we were never, all the time I worked on it, told by the administration to do anything to censor the publication.
Now, there are certain ground rules that were set down for us to operate under, and we didn't want the editor of The Bat, for instance, to just go out and tear the university to pieces.
One or two editors took it on themselves to slaughter the cadet corps.
And we didn't think they had a right to slaughter the cadets.
So we, as a publication board, told them, as long as you fare and stick by the truth 100%, we can't tell you you can't do this.
But what are you trying to accomplish?
And they'd come around and see this.
We did it by advisement.
One or two of them we had to order not to do it, to leave out certain things.
And they'd come down and jump the president
We didn't think that it was quite cricket for the publications to tear the president to pieces because this paper goes all over the state.
And so far as I know, the publications, two publications have been working better here than any other institution I know of.
I know I read the paper about all the trouble they have over at Austin, and it's constant.
Rice, not a very big institution, they have trouble.
University of Houston.
Harvard even had trouble with their lampoon and some other publications.
A&M hadn't had that kind of trouble.
Now, one other thing that I observed, A&M has spent a lot of time working with

all state and federal agencies to get facilities for proper research, and we've gotten money and equipment from some of these firms and institutions, and I think ANM made real good progress with its program.
Sometimes I hear various people in the faculty say we're spending too much on research, and I don't know whether it's true or not, but we need research, and it's expensive,
But everything about the university expansion, and if I had any complaint to make now that I didn't make in 1945, is that the people have become more wasteful.
The university people, when I came in in 45, were penurious, really.
Had to be, because they didn't have the money.
And they used pieces of paper, scrap paper, that normally you throw in the trash.
And I see people now using letterhead stationery to write notes and pencil notes on and paper, I mean, telephone numbers and things.
To me, this is a waste.
And I see people making trips just for the trip purpose, not to benefit the university.
Now, this didn't happen 20 years ago.
But this has been a change in all government agencies.
People travel a whole lot.
People become wasteful, and you have an assistant, and then an assistant to the assistant.
You need some of these people, but a lot of them you don't need.
And this has become big business, really.
So I'm afraid sometimes that when an institution like A&M over expands, I don't know what the student enrollment was last year, 17,000?
It's been up as high as 18, I think.
That's pretty big.
That's a lot of people, and you just don't have the facilities to take care of them.
At least you can't take care of them anymore.
No, Cooper says it'll probably be 22,000 next year.
That's right.
Now, where are you going to put them?
You don't have any supervision on them when they live downtown.
They may be on marijuana or morphine or codeine or something.
You don't know what they're doing.
They may be prostituting, they may be stealing, they could be doing a lot of things.
You can't say they're not doing that on the campus, because I saw all those things done when I was a student.
Not very many of them, and a lot of them were picked up and talked to, and some of them were punished, some of them were sent home.
But you don't even see them anymore.
And the teacher has so many classes and so many students, a lot of times he just knows them by numbers.
And I taught school a long time.
I knew my students.
I knew a lot about their families.
This is good because I knew why he revolted when I wanted to make a B, when he wanted to make a D. I knew his background.
Well, you can't do that in a big institution.
And this makes it cost a lot.
American people have become

very fluid and wasteful we're wasting lots of good resources we're wasting lives we're wasting paper and trees concrete and other things so this is the thing we've got to keep in mind when we talk about students because they they they see these things happening back in the public school back in the city government back at home
I just got back from San Antonio, and my grandson, 18-year-old high school kid, got one year in high school.
He wants to go to A&M, incidentally.
He wants to play football.
He's a pretty good athlete, but he wants a car.
So his father told him, Robert, if you can make enough money this summer to buy a car, fine, but I'm not going to make any note for you.
Now, a lot of his friends had new cars.
Papa bought it for
Well, he doesn't need a car.
It's good to have, but he doesn't really need it.
He could ride the school bus from his front door, well, one block up to the school back, but he wants to go in his own car.
This is expensive.
Well, if you go staying in, he'll demand more than I demanded when I was a student, and more than his father did when he was a student here.
So this is a trend in America.
But I think all in all, I'm sorry I don't know anything much about Williams.
I know him, I've seen him, met him twice.
He wouldn't know me if he'd see me today.
I knew Kodas by reputation only when he was at Arkansas and East Texas.
He comes with good reputation, so he ought to be a good dean of students.
give us any more about General Rudder as president?
Any personal remembrances that you have?
Yeah, I thought Mr.
Rudder was an outstanding man.
He certainly wasn't what you'd normally call an educator, because in the first place, he didn't have a whole lot of education himself, except what he made, his own self-education.
But he understood
how to find out about problems, and he went about it and found out.
Sometimes he was pretty ruthless and cold-blooded about it, but he found out what the problems were at A&M.
And then he set about trying to remedy the problems, check if he needed facilities.
He knew where he'd go and get them.
And he selected people like Dr. Settle, for instance.
I know one of the reasons he brought Dr. Settle here is because he had good contact with the federal government.
And Settle was a good research man, had this reputation.
So he hired Suttle and turned him loose.
And Suttle went after the state in Washington quite a bit.
And not only in Washington, but everywhere.
He tried to pick people that had some organizational ability and guts enough to do what they thought was right and would have a certain amount of allegiance to the university and to him.
in my opinion, bad selections, but every leader's got to do some bad selections.
I thought once or twice that he picked too many ex-military people just because they were military to be staff people.
But most of them turned out to be real good people, real proficient and dedicated to A&M.
Some of them are still here.
And a lot of the non-military believers detested him for this, which wasn't fair.
They were just biased and they were super critical.
But he didn't matter with the education part of it.
He let the deans do this because that's what they're hard to do anyhow.
He went about raising money and organizing and setting up procedures and systems.
And if he thought he could go to Washington and talk to somebody up there and get some help, he did it.
If he wanted to go to Atlanta, Georgia and meet some people that were around him, he got a man set up there in the, what is that office where you go out and beg for money?
The development office?
The development office.
He said, I have a good system there, and he helps them.
When old Walker wants to go to see Sid Cowell, Sid Cowell got
million dollars he wants to give to the university, and with a little drag on his feet, rather go see him.
Just get in his plane or car and drive down and see him.
He didn't hesitate to call Tiger Teague or somebody else in Washington, some general that he knew up there, or somebody in California.
And I thought he was fair, fair to the student, fair to the staff.
He got better pay for them.
tried to improve the facilities.
He didn't hesitate.
He said, sure, it's a poor man's school, but we can't be paupers.
We've got to build better places to live.
And he set up a good system for building better buildings.
And they had discarded the idea of air conditioning these old buildings.
And Rutter said, I'm not going to take that.
And he pointed to Dean Benson and said, Dean, I want you to get with some experts.
Bible, Hollis Bible, for instance.
Bring him up here and make a survey.
And then if you all tell me that it can't be done, I'll buy it.
But in two years' time, he had all the old bellies air conditioned.
Because he just didn't take no.
Now, I didn't think he could do it either.
But it worked out real good.
He got a lot of prestige for A&M because he'd go and speak for A&M wherever he went.
I think people generally here and away from the university had a great deal of respect for Earl Rudder.
And I think it would be a long time before they got a man to replace him.
He didn't have a doctor's degree and all that, but he was a smart cookie.
He knew people pretty well, and he knew how to get things done, and he worked hard.
In fact, I wouldn't be surprised if he did.
He worked too hard and didn't take care of his health like he should have.
And died at a reasonably young age.
And I think if he'd have stayed here another 10 years until his retirement time, it wouldn't have been quite 10 years, but I think he would have done terrific things for A&M.
Maybe somebody else can, too.
Nobody's indispensable, but I thought he was real, real excellent for Texas A&M.
Now, at the University of Texas, he probably wouldn't have been worth anything.
But he was an ex-Aggie, and this helped him.
And he had the respect of the military people in the United States because he'd been a general.
Was a colonel in combat, a lieutenant colonel in combat.
And they proved that he could organize from scratch to confounded, compounded, fighting in it.
He did it.
This helped him.
And then he took that land office when he was in trouble, bailed it out.
And this balance had been difficult.
I have a question.
I just wondered, do you believe he ever had any political aspirations?
I've heard it rumored that he might have liked to run for office.
Yes, in fact, I heard quite often when he first came here that he came here with the hope that he would eventually jump to be governor of Texas.
I heard this.
And then I also heard once or twice that he had some aspirations about being a federal politician.
Possibly running for the Senate?
Yes.
But I sort of doubt this because I've talked to him many times.
In fact, I asked him about it.
Point blank, did you have any political aspirations?
Now, some people here still believe that he did.
In fact, I talked to a man yesterday that said he believed that Ernie Rudder came here with that in mind.
And he had this from some people in Austin.
I said, well, they were just guessing, I'll bet you.
Now, maybe he did.
I don't know.
But if he did, he should have dragged his feet a long time.
Yeah, it is interesting.
I just wonder whether that was a rumor or maybe he ever, he really did want to run for office.
I know he did a very good job when he was in the land office.
Yes.
And built a fairly healthy respect.
Well, he was elected one time, wasn't he?
Yes, he was.
He was appointed to take a vacation, then he was elected.
Well, he might have been, I don't know, but he told me that he didn't have any ambition to be governor of Texas or a senator.
No, you can't tell.
I don't know.
Now, he was mayor of Brady, wasn't he?
Gee, I think so.
I think so.
Which nothing really politically.
No, no, no.
It's not.
I know that.
It's just interesting.
I'm wondering whether his career was cut short here or was cut short for a bigger.
He had bigger things in mind.
I really believe the reason...
I got awful upset at Mr. Rutter back at the time Com left here, because as I told you yesterday, Mr. Rutter had been to A&M when they didn't have any student services.
Everything was done by the Commandant's Office.
And then further, he was an athlete, and athletes didn't do a lot of things that regular cadets did.
They lived a sort of secluded life,
They always did, even back when I was in school.
So when he came here, he come left, and Mr. Rutter told me that he believed he didn't see any sense in that organization.
He said, go wipe it out.
And I said, sir, you wipe it out, and you're going to see how fast A&M folds up.
Because the commandant has positive orders from the military that he cannot keep A&M's dirty linen clean.
Now, I don't like to use dirty linen because everything that you do in a student life, people associate with violence and crime.
But I'd say 90% of the things that student personnel service people do don't have anything to do with rules and regulations and violations.
So he said, well, what do you do?
And I told him.
I wrote out a whole page of things and outlined for him what to do.
He said, draw me a diagram of what ought to be.
And just behind he, so he finally asked me, if we make you dean, what'd you do?
And I said, no, I don't want to be the dean.
And he asked me why.
He smiled and said, well, that to me sounds silly, but I'll buy that.
So two days later, he called back and said, I'll change my mind.
I've talked to some other people, and I think we're going to keep some semblance, and I'd like to have you stay on as the director of student personnel services.
Not a dean, but a director.

And the reason was I had told him that if I take it on and do it like I thought it ought to be, there are about seven or eight people that I'd have to fire for inefficiency, but they were all good friends of mine, and I wasn't going to fire them because I didn't hire them.
So he got mad at me, said, he said, trouble is you don't have gut enough to do it.
I said, hell, I don't.
I got gut enough to do it.
I'm just not going to do it.
I don't believe in operating like that.
So I got real mad at him.
And I went back to see him later, and he laughed and said, you got mad, didn't you?
And I said, yeah, I got mad, sure.
I didn't like your attitude.
So he said, I didn't like yours either.
But anyhow, we got it all settled.
And he told me just a short while, four hours ahead.
In fact, I had a heart attack.
And he came down to the hospital to see me.
And he came over and put his hand on my shoulder and said, don't worry about your job.
We'll take care of it if I have to do it myself until you get back.
And when I got ready to retire, he came over.
and talked to me a long time about the Student Life Program.
And he said he'd changed his mind about a lot of things at A&M since he'd been working here.

And one of the things was that he knew that we needed to have good planning and good leadership in the Student Life Program at Texas A&M, just as much so as we did in the dean's office in veterinary college and architecture and so on.
And he saw a lot of things that needed to be done, and he said, I'm going to keep on.
